response:
So we need to find the determinant of matrix $\mathbf{R}$</think> While Matrix $\mathbf{R}$ has a special name, namely the rotation matrix, it does not really matter what it is called. In my mind, the relevant work is completing $R(\pi/2, 0, 0)$ but this is not the right way to be thinking. All we are really given is the angle which indicates that the axis of rotation is aligned with the $x$-axis.
We cannot simply say "$rotation matrix$" and move on, because rotation matrices do not have a very general form. A matrix $R(\theta, \mathbf{u})$ that rotates a matrix $v$ by an angle $\theta$ around a vector $\mathbf{u}$ has no special structure that we can utilize.
Rather, we know properties of the matrix. If it doesn't have a special name, it's the matrix that transforms all vectors by conjugation. Many properties of a matrix can be used to understand a matrix, even if there are several operations that lead to the same results. In this case, the important properties of $R(\pi/2, x)$ are as follows:
\begin{align} 
R(\pi/2, x) x &= x \\ \\
\left [ R(\pi/2,x) \right ]^{-1} x &= \frac{-x}{\sqrt{2}} \\ \\
\text{when the initial vector is perpendicular to $x \quad$  } R(\pi/2, x) v &= \begin{bmatrix}-v\\\sqrt{2}\end{bmatrix}\\ \\
R(\pi, x,\mathbb{R}^3) &= -I \\ \\
R(\pi/2, x) y &= \frac{y} {\|y\| } \end{align}
We can also notice that
\begin{align} 
\textbf{e} &= \mathbf{R} [\mathbf{i}]_\times^\perp \\ \\
R[\mathbf{L}]_\times^\perp R &= [\mathbf{L}]_\times^\perp \text{where $\mathbf{L}$ is the vector $\textbf{e}$}\\
\end{align}
Determinants do not commute; however when given a diagonal matrix or a linearnear map holding orthogonal basis vectors you can use the determinant property $$\det (AB)=\det(A) \det(B)$$ To find $\det R$
\begin{align} 
G &=\operatorname{diag} \left(\begin{bmatrix} 1&0&q\\q&R \end{bmatrix}\right)\left(\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0\end{bmatrix}\right) \\ \\
&=\begin{bmatrix} 1&0&q\\q&1 \end{bmatrix} \end{align}
Since $G=\operatorname{diag}(A\mathbf{e})$ where $\mathbf{e}$ is perpendicular to $A \in \mathbb{R}^{2x2}$, 
\begin{align} \det(A_2)&=\det(G\mathbf{e}) \\ \\
&=\det (G)\det (\mathbf{e})\\ \\
&=\det (G)=\left(\det\begin{bmatrix} 1&0&q\\ q&1\end{bmatrix}\right)\left(\det \begin{bmatrix} q&1\\ \end{bmatrix}\right)=q^2 + 1\end{align}     
\begin{align}R&=
\begin{bmatrix}
    \cos(\theta)&-\sin(\theta)\\
    \sin(\theta)&\cos(\theta) \\
\end{bmatrix}_{3x3}\\
\det R&=1\end{align}
Answer: Answer templates are automatically expanded to include question marks, i.e., \det \mathbf{R}.

