Denote by D' the point on AC such that D'F is parallel to BC. Then [[Angle bisector theorem]] gives [[AA similarity]]$\triangle{AFD}\cong \triangle AD'C,\frac{AF}{AB}=\frac{FD}{D'C}.  \frac{AF}{AT}=\frac{FD}{D'C}$


[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

pair A, B, C, D, E, F, T,DD';

B = (0,0);
C = (5,0);
A = intersectionpoint(arc(B,4,0,180),arc(C,6,0,180));
D = interp(A,B,1/4);
E = interp(A,C,2/6);
T = extension(A, incenter(A,B,C), B, C);
P = interp(D,(1/3)*C,1/2);
F = P;

DD' = extension(A,T,P,(1/3)*B + (2/3)*C);

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(A--T);
draw(D--E);

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$D$", D, W);
label("$E$", E, NE);
label("$F$", F, SW);
label("$T$", T, S);
label("$D'$", D', NW);
[/asy]
Let $D'$ be the point on $AC$ such that $D'F$ is parallel to $BC$.  Note that $\triangle{AFD} \sim \triangle{AD'C}$ by AA (∠$ADF$ and ∠$ACD'$ are corresponding angles in parallels and ∠$ADC$ and ∠$AD'C$ are vertical angles).  Thus, $\frac{AF}{AB} = \frac{FD}{D'C}$ and since $\frac{AT}{A' T} = \frac{AD}{A D'}$, we have $\frac{AF}{AT} = \frac{FD}{D'C}$

